## Part 3: Step-by-Step Fixes for PodNotReady
When you receive a PodNotReady alarm on your phone, copy and paste these exact commands into your terminal to diagnose and fix the problem.
## Step 1: Find the broken pod
Run this command to see a list of applications. Look at the STATUS or READY column to find the one showing errors.

kubectl get pods -n <namespace>


* What to look for: Look for statuses like CrashLoopBackOff, ImagePullBackOff, or Error.

## Step 2: Check the recent history
Run this command to see the timeline of events for that specific application container.

kubectl describe pod <pod-name> -n <namespace>


* How to read the output: Scroll down to the very bottom and look at the Events section. It will explicitly tell you if the system ran out of memory (OOMKilled) or if the network failed.

## Step 3: Read the application print logs
Run this command to read the exact error message printout from inside the code.

kubectl logs <pod-name> -n <namespace> --tail=100


* How to read the output: Look at the last 100 lines for programming code errors, missing database connection keys, or password failures.

## Step 4: Common fixes you can try
If you find the issue using the steps above, try these quick remediation actions:

* If the application is frozen: Force it to reboot by deleting it. Kubernetes will immediately start a fresh, new one automatically:

kubectl delete pod <pod-name> -n <namespace>

* If it ran out of memory (OOMKilled): You need to give it more room to breathe. Edit the deployment file and increase the memory configurations:

kubectl edit deployment <deployment-name> -n <namespace>

(Scroll to the resources.limits.memory section and change it to a higher number, like changing 2Gi to 4Gi).







